        "title": "Reception at Antioch — encouragement, joy, prophetic strengthening",
        "range": "15:30-35",
        "excerpt": "When they had read it, they rejoiced because of its encouragement.",
        "body": "The decree's reception at Antioch is Luke's confirmation that the verdict was right. Doctrine recognized as gospel-faithful produces joy in those who had been disturbed; doctrine that capitulates to legalism produces bondage. The Antioch reception is the test case for the decree's gospel-fidelity.\n\n*So when they were sent away, they went down to Antioch* (15:30) — the geographical reversal of 15:2's *go up to Jerusalem*. *And having gathered the congregation* (*plēthos* — the whole assembly, not just leadership) *they delivered the letter*. The communication is public, transparent, and corporate. Then (15:31): *when they had read it, they rejoiced because of its encouragement* (*ēcharesan epi tē paraklēsei*). Note the cause of the joy — not freedom from rules in some libertine sense, but freedom from a yoke that was crushing them. The decree did not relax discipleship; it disentangled grace from legalism. The joy is the joy of being *received* without prerequisite, of hearing apostolic confirmation that one is genuinely a child of God by faith alone in Christ alone.\n\nJudas and Silas extend the moment (15:32) — *being prophets themselves* — by *a lengthy message* (*logou pollou*) of further encouragement and strengthening (*epestērixan*, the same root used later in 15:41 for Paul's work). The prophetic ministry confirms the apostolic ruling. The Antiochene Gentile believers are not merely told *you are accepted*; they are catechized, strengthened, built up in the doctrinal soil the decree has prepared.\n\nThe parenthetical about Silas in 15:34 (bracketed in NASB as a variant) prepares for 15:40 — Silas remains available in Antioch when the second journey begins. *Paul and Barnabas stayed in Antioch* (15:35) — the established missionary base — *teaching and preaching the word of the Lord with many others also*. Antioch is by AD 49 a substantial multi-leader congregation; Paul and Barnabas are part of a broader teaching collective. The chapter closes its primary movement here: crisis resolved, congregation strengthened, gospel preserved. Luke's narrative breath is restored.\n\n> **Greek note.** *Paraklēsis* (encouragement, 15:31) is the Spirit-given word of comfort and exhortation (the same root as *Paraklētos*, the Spirit's name in John 14-16). *Epistērizō* (15:32, 41) — to confirm, prop up, settle further — is one of Luke's favorite ministry verbs (Acts 14:22; 18:23). The decree did not merely permit; it built up."
